  "prompt": "How does CB Antenna work?",
  "response": "A CB (Citizens Band) antenna works by transmitting and receiving radio signals in the Citizens Band radio frequency range (typically 26.965 to 27.405 MHz). Here's a basic overview of how it functions:\n\n1. Signal Transmission:\n- The antenna converts electrical signals from the radio into electromagnetic waves\n- These waves are radiated into the surrounding space\n- The antenna's length is typically designed to match the wavelength of CB radio frequencies\n\n2. Signal Reception:\n- Incoming electromagnetic waves induce electrical currents in the antenna\n- These currents are then converted back into electrical signals by the radio\n\n3. Key Characteristics:\n- Typically vertically polarized\n- Common types include:\n  \u2022 Whip antennas\n  \u2022 Base-loaded antennas\n  \u2022 Center-loaded antennas\n  \u2022 Fiberglass antennas\n\n4. Performance Factors:\n- Antenna length\n- Mounting location\n- Ground plane\n- SWR (Standing Wave Ratio)\n- Antenna design\n\n5. Radiation Pattern:\n- Omnidirectional radiation\n- Signals propagate in a roughly circular pattern around the antenna\n\nThe antenna's design and installation significantly impact the radio's communication range and signal quality.",
